        let foodDescriptionArray = ["escolar": "Pregnant women should not eat escolar because it may contain indigestible wax ester that causes digestion problems and diarrhea according to <a href=\"http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/content/cda-pubs-cdi-2002-cdi2603-htm-cdi2603i.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Health.gov.au</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "arugula": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/349069-salads-safe-eat-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, arugula is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their arugula prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "halibut": "Pregnant women can enjoy halibut as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Halibut is in the class of fish considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat halibut if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "imitation crabmeat": "Pregnant women can enjoy imitation crabmeat as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week if it is made from Hake or other low mercury fish. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby.&nbsp;Additionally, pregnant women should only eat imitation crabmeat if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "liver sausage": "Pregnant women should not consume liver according to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/it-safe-eat-liver-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.marchofdimes.com/pregnancy/nutrition_risks.html\" target=\"_blank\">March of Dimes</a>. Some studies have shown that the high amounts of vitamin A in liver may cause birth defects.&nbsp;#@:", "chicken sausage": "Pregnant women can enjoy sausage if heated until steaming hot and is at least 165&deg;F, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/529426-is-it-okay-to-eat-hot-sausage-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. Undercooked or raw sausage may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/291530-sodium-nitrate-consumption-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a> also advises that pregnant women should stay away from products that contain nitrates and nitrites. #@:", "lamb chops": "Pregnant women can enjoy lamb chops if they are fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook lamb chops to at least 145&deg;F with a three-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked lamb.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "chicken": "Pregnant women can enjoy chicken if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook chicken to at least 165&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked chicken.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "ceviche": "Pregnant women can enjoy ceviche if it is made with cooked seafood. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F. Pregnant women should confirm that they can eat the seafood in the ceviche by searching for the ingredients in the search window above. &nbsp;#@:", "fortified cereals": "Fortified cereals are a safe choice during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/381845-the-best-non-fattening-diet-for-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "philly cheese steak": "Pregnant women can enjoy philly cheese steak if it is made with steak that is fully cooked and safe cheese. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook steak to at least 145&deg;F with a three-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked beef. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "catfish": "Pregnant women can enjoy catfish as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;catfish is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat catfish if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "onions": "Onions are a safe choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their onions prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "potatoes": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/522547-can-pregnant-women-eat-potatoes/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, potatoes are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their potatoes prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "cod": "Pregnant women can enjoy cod as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Cod is in the class of fish that is considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat cod if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "curry powder": "Curry powder is safe to eat during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/432705-curry-powder-and-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. However, eating spicy foods such as curry may cause discomfort during digestion for some pregnant women.&nbsp;#@:", "grapefruit juice": "Grapefruit juice is safe during pregnancy if it is pasteurized, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/441703-is-it-safe-to-drink-red-grapefruit-juice-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> states that fresh-squeezed juice may not always be pasteurized, which means that harmful bacteria like Salmonella and E. Coli may be present in the juice. Pregnant women should avoid fresh juice without a label stating that it is pasteurized.#@:", "swiss chard": "Swiss Chard is a healthy and safe food choice during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.pregnancyandbaby.com/pregnancy/articles/945615/10-foods-every-pregnant-woman-should-eat\" target=\"_blank\">Pregnancy and Baby</a>. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their swiss chard before eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "bread": "Bread is a safe choice during pregnancy according to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/pregnancy-nutrition/PR00108\" target=\"_blank\">Mayo Clinic</a>. Whole wheat bread and whole grain bread are nutritious choices.&nbsp;#@:", "eggplant": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/496031-eating-eggplant-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, cooked eggplant is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. Raw eggplant, however, is not recommended for pregnant women because it may cause digestion issues. It is essential that pregnant women wash their eggplant prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "gruyere cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Gruyere Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "aioli sauce": "Aioli made with raw eggs, often found in restaurants, is not safe for pregnant women to eat, according to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\">WebMd</a>.&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\">BabyMed </a>and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a> state that raw eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby.&nbsp; However, aioli made with pasteurized eggs is safe for pregnant women to ingest.#@:", "plaice": "Pregnant women can enjoy plaice as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;plaice is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat plaice if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "tofu": "Tofu is considered safe for pregnant women according to <a href=\"http://www.fitpregnancy.com/nutrition-recipes/prenatal-nutrition/soy-safety\" target=\"_blank\">Fit Pregnancy</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/377222-can-you-eat-soy-protein-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "flounder": "Pregnant women can enjoy flounder as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;flounder is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat flounder if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "parmesan cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Parmesan Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;#@:", "trout": "Pregnant women can enjoy trout (freshwater) as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;trout is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat trout if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "ground chicken": "Pregnant women can enjoy ground chicken if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook ground chicken to at least 165&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked chicken.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "zucchini": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_10-fast-foods-a-pregnant-woman-could-love-and-five-to-avoid_1313899.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/516976-are-zucchini-squash-ok-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, zucchini is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their zucchini before eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "juice (fresh squeezed)": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>,&nbsp;fresh-squeezed juice may not always be pasteurized, which means that harmful bacteria like Salmonella and E. Coli may be present in the juice. Pregnant women should avoid fresh juice without a label stating that it is pasteurized.#@:", "vodka": "Pregnant women should not drink vodka. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, there is no amount of alcohol that is considered safe during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "fava beans": "Fava beans are a safe option for pregnant women according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/349074-nutrition-information-for-escarole/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. It is essential that pregnant women wash their fava beans prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "beef liver": "Pregnant women should not consume liver according to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/it-safe-eat-liver-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.marchofdimes.com/pregnancy/nutrition_risks.html\" target=\"_blank\">March of Dimes</a>. Some studies have shown that the high amounts of vitamin A in liver may cause birth defects.&nbsp;#@:", "escarole": "Escarole is a safe option for pregnant women according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/349074-nutrition-information-for-escarole/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. It is essential that pregnant women wash their escarole prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "pork chops": "Pregnant women can enjoy pork chops if they are fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook pork to at least 145&deg;F with a 3-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked pork. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "prunes": "Prunes are safe to eat during pregnancy. Prunes contain high amounts of Potassium, which according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/556102-a-natural-food-good-for-swelling-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, helps remedy swelling and constipation during pregnancy.#@:", "radishes": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/503658-can-pregnant-women-eat-radishes/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, radishes are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their radishes prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "balsamic vinegar": "There has been some controversy regarding the safety of balsamic vinegar during pregnancy due to possible lead content and/or poisining according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/445957-is-balsamic-vinegar-dressing-okay-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. Many manufecturers provide information concerning any possible lead content in their vinegar on their labels. Be aware of the risk and talk to your doctor to ensure the vinegar you intend to eat is safe during pregnancy.#@:", "tomme cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Tomme Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>. Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "chevre cheese": "Soft cheeses such as Chevre Cheese are generally considered unsafe for pregnant women according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a> &nbsp;Soft cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "coffee": "There have been many opposing studies regarding the safety of caffeine intake during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;caffeine is permitted during pregnancy but intake should be limited to under 200mg per day. However, some sources suggest to avoid all caffeinated products during the first trimester of pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "brie cheese": "Non-imported Brie made with pasteurized milk is considered safe for pregnant women according to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. However, pregnant women should avoid&nbsp;Brie made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "colby cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Colby Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "kola nut": "Kola Nut is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "stilton cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Stilton Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>. Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "sunflower seeds": "Sunflower seeds are a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. Sunflower seeds are high in fiber and can relieve constipation if eaten during pregnancy.#@:", "kabocha squash": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/516976-are-zucchini-squash-ok-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, squash is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their squash prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "romaine lettuce": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/349069-salads-safe-eat-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, romaine lettuce is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their romaine lettuce prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "romano cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Romano Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;#@:", "bluefish": "Pregnant women can enjoy bluefish as part of the three six-ounce servings of high mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Bluefish is in the class of fish considered to have a high amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat bluefish if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145 &deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "mascarpone cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/156297-mascarpone-cheese-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/listeria.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, Mascarpone Cheese is considered safe for pregnant women if it is pasteurized.&nbsp;#@:", "strawberries": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, strawberries are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their strawberries prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "oysters (raw)": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should avoid eating raw or undercooked shellfish. #@:", "steak": "Pregnant women can enjoy steak if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook steak to at least 145&deg;F with a three-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked steak.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "lentils": "Lentils are a safe and healthy option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.parents.com/pregnancy/my-body/nutrition/5-great-pregnancy-foods/\" target=\"_blank\">Parents.com</a> and are a great source of folate, iron, and protein.#@:", "endive": "Endive is a safe option for pregnant women. It is essential that pregnant women wash their endive prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "sole": "Pregnant women can enjoy sole as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;sole is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat sole if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "lemons": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/395906-eating-lemon-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, lemons are a safe and healthy option during pregnancy. However, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/262204-foods-to-avoid-in-pregnancy-with-indigestion/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, the high acidity in lemons may cause indigestion and eat away the enamel of teeth during pregnancy. It is essential that pregnant women wash their lemons prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "snapper": "Pregnant women can enjoy snapper as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Snapper is in the class of fish considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat snapper if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "tangerines": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, tangerines are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their tangerines prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "havarti cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Havarti Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "cyclamate": "The <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>&nbsp;advises that pregnant women avoid the sweetener cyclamate.#@:", "apple cider": "Apple cider is safe during pregnancy if it is pasteurized according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/490408-apple-cider-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> writes that fresh-squeezed juice may not always be pasteurized, which means that harmful bacteria like Salmonella and E. Coli may be present in the juice. Pregnant women should avoid fresh juice without a label stating that it is pasteurized.&nbsp;#@:", "dried bananas": "Dried bananas are considered safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "hemp seeds": "Hemp Seeds are a safe choice during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/282451-a-list-of-vegan-super-foods-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "cereals": "Cereals are a safe choice during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/381845-the-best-non-fattening-diet-for-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "leftovers": "According the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, food that is refrigerated after being cooked needs to be reheated to&nbsp;165&ordm; F. Sauces, soups, or gravies should be reheated until boiling. Perishable foods should be stored in a refrigirator or freezer as soon as possible, and always within 2 hours. For air temperatures 90&ordm; F or higher, &nbsp;leftovers should be stored within an hour. #@:", "grapefruit": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>, grapefruit are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their grapefruit prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "parsnips": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/349069-salads-safe-eat-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, parsnips are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their parsnips prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "bell peppers": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/nutrientsvitaminspregnancy.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, bell peppers are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their bell peppers prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "bacon": "Pregnant women can enjoy bacon if it is fully cooked and does not contain nitrates or nitrites. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook pork to at least 160&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked bacon. <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/513685-bacon-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong </a>states that bacon should be cooked until it is crispy and red in color and should be inspected for any spots where it was not cooked all the way through.&nbsp;#@:", "raisins": "Raisins are safe to eat during pregnancy. Raisins are high in fiber and can relieve constipation during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "croaker": "Pregnant women can enjoy croaker as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Croaker is in the class of fish that is considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat croaker if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "butterfish": "Pregnant women can enjoy butterfish as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;butterfish is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat butterfish if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "saw palmetto": "Saw Palmetto is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "blackberries": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, blackberries are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their blackberries prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "chaumes cheese": "Soft cheeses such as Chaumes Cheese are generally considered unsafe for pregnant women according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a> &nbsp;Soft cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "watercress": "Watercress is a safe option during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their watercress prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "gouda cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Gouda Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "mahi-mahi": "Pregnant women can enjoy mahi-mahi as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Mahi-mahi is in the class of fish considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat mahi-mahi if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "blackstrap molasses": "According to <a href=\"http://www.fitpregnancy.com/nutrition-recipes/prenatal-nutrition/10-surprising-prenatal-power-foods?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">Fit Pregnancy</a>, blackstrap molasses is a safe choice during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "nova style seafood": "Pregnant women should not eat nova style seafood. According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, nova style seafood could contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.&nbsp;#@:", "lamb shank": "Pregnant women can enjoy lamb shank if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook lamb shank to at least 145&deg;F with a three-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked lamb.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "saccharin (sweet ™n low)": "The <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>&nbsp;advises that pregnant women avoid the sweetener saccharin (Sweet \'N Low) .#@:", "grape juice": "Grape juice is safe during pregnancy if it is pasteurized, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/312065-healthy-fruit-juices-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> states that fresh-squeezed juice may not always be pasteurized, which means that harmful bacteria like Salmonella and E. Coli may be present in the juice. Pregnant women should avoid fresh juice without a label stating that it is pasteurized.#@:", "wine": "Pregnant women should not drink wine. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, there is no amount of alcohol that is considered safe during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "cottage cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">t</a>he <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/listeria.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, Cottage Cheese is considered safe for pregnant women if it is pasteurized or is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;#@:", "kanpachi": "Pregnant women should not eat Kanpachi (also known as very young yellowtail). Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/sushimercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;Kanpachi is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "buri (adult yellowtail)": "Pregnant women should not eat buri (also known as adult yellowtail). Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/sushimercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, buri is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "pyramide cheese": "Soft cheeses such as Pyramide Cheese are generally considered unsafe for pregnant women according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a> &nbsp;Soft cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "mousse": "Mousse that is made with pasteurized eggs and is fully cooked is safe to eat. <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\">BabyMed </a>and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a> state that raw or unpasteurized eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby. #@:", "green beans (string beans hericot vert)": "According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/nutrientsvitaminspregnancy.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, green beans are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their beans prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "pasta": "According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/health/treatments/healthy_living/nutrition/life_preconcpreg.shtml\" target=\"_blank\">BBC</a>, pasta is a safe option during pregnancy.#@:", "gorgonzola cheese": "Non-imported Gorgonzola Cheese made with pasteurized milk is considered safe for pregnant women according to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. However, pregnant women should avoid&nbsp;Gorgonzola Cheese made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "quinoa": "Quinoa is a safe choice during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/282451-a-list-of-vegan-super-foods-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "oysters (cooked)": "Pregnant women can enjoy cooked oysters as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;oysters are in the class of seafood considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat oysters if they are fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook oysters until the shells open. If the shells do not open, those oysters should be discarded. &nbsp;#@:", "pate": "Pregnant women should not eat pate according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a> and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/can-you-have-pate-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>. <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/it-safe-eat-liver-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.marchofdimes.com/pregnancy/nutrition_risks.html\" target=\"_blank\">March of Dimes</a>&nbsp;state that pregnant women should not consume liver products.&nbsp;Some studies have shown that the high amounts of vitamin A in liver may cause birth defects.&nbsp;#@:", "sashimi": "Pregnant women should not eat sashimi. Sashimi is usually made with raw or undercooked fish. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F. &nbsp;#@:", "guarana": "Guarana is unsafe to eat during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "roast beef": "Pregnant women can eat deli meats, such as roast beef, if they are reheated until steaming hot or 165&deg;F according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/356258-can-you-eat-roast-beef-deli-meat-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, the <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/features/pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">CDC</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>. According to the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, deli meats may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. Listeria grows on meat at refrigirator temperatures.&nbsp;#@:", "asparagus": "Asparagus is safe to eat&nbsp;during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their asparagus prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "theobromine (cocoa extract)": "Theobromine (cocoa extract) is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "cold cuts": "Pregnant women can eat cold cuts if they are reheated until steaming hot or 165&deg;F and if they do not contain nitrates or nitrites, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/372099-can-pregnant-women-eat-deli-meat/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, the <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/features/pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">CDC</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>. According to the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, cold cuts may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. Listeria grows on meat at refrigirator temperatures.&nbsp;#@:", "dried blueberries": "Dried blueberries are considered safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "apples": "According to <a href=\"http://www.eatright.org/Public/content.aspx?id=6808\" target=\"_blank\">Eatright.org</a>, apples are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their apples prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "filtered water": "According to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=2\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>,&nbsp;filtered water is a safe option during pregnancy.#@:", "gravy": "Gravy is a safe option during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/guide/healthy-weight-gain\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "shropshire blue cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Shropshire Blue Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>. Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "caffeine": "There have been many opposing studies regarding the safety of caffeine intake during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;caffeine is permitted during pregnancy but intake should be limited to under 200mg per day. However, some sources suggest to avoid all caffeinated products during the first trimester of pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "raw fish": "Pregnant women should not eat raw fish. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "ginger": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/535929-is-ginger-safe-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, ginger is essentially a safe choice during pregnancy. However, the use of ginger is controversial and there have been studies that showed that ginger may alter the sex hormones in fetuses. Out of an abundance of caution, pregnant women should consult their healthcare provider to make sure ginger is safe to eat.#@:", "ricotta cheese": "Non-imported Ricotta Cheese made with pasteurized milk is considered safe for pregnant women according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/361380-can-you-eat-ricotta-cheese-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a> and the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. However, pregnant women should avoid&nbsp;Ricotta Cheese made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "squid": "Pregnant women can enjoy squid as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;squid is in the class of seafood considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat squid if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "white wine": "Pregnant women should not drink white wine. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, there is no amount of alcohol that is considered safe during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "smoked salmon (lox)": "Pregnant women should not eat smoked salmon (also known as lox). According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, smoked salmon could contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.&nbsp;#@:", "apricots": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>, apricots are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their apricots prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "chicken liver": "Pregnant women should not consume chicken liver according to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/it-safe-eat-liver-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.marchofdimes.com/pregnancy/nutrition_risks.html\" target=\"_blank\">March of Dimes</a>. Some studies have shown that the high amounts of vitamin A in liver may cause birth defects.&nbsp;#@:", "tuna tartare": "Pregnant women should not eat tuna tartare. Tuna tartare usually made with raw or undercooked tuna. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F. &nbsp;#@:", "ice cream": "Ice cream made with pasteurized milk is considered safe during pregnancy. However, ice cream made with raw and/or unpasteurized milk is generally considered unsafe during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "papayas": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, papayas are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their papayas prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.&nbsp;#@:", "inada": "Pregnant women should not eat Inada (also known as very young yellowtail). Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/sushimercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, Inada is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "duck": "Pregnant women can enjoy duck if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook duck to at least 165&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked duck.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "rudderfish": "Pregnant women should not eat rudderfish because it may contain indigestible wax ester that causes digestion problems and diarrhea according to <a href=\"http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/content/cda-pubs-cdi-2002-cdi2603-htm-cdi2603i.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Health.gov.au</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "shark": "Pregnant women should not eat shark. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;shark is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "beets": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/349069-salads-safe-eat-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, beets are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their beets prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "greek yogurt": "Greek yogurt made with pasteurized milk is safe for pregnant women according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/440815-greek-yogurt-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. However, yogurt made with unpasteurized milk is considered unsafe during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "asadero cheese": "Non-imported Asadero Cheese made with pasteurized milk is considered safe for pregnant women according to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm106913.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>.&nbsp;However, pregnant women should avoid&nbsp;Asadero Cheese made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "salmon": "Pregnant women can enjoy salmon as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;salmon is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat salmon if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "oatmeal": "Oatmeal is a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. Oatmeal is high in fiber and can relieve constipation if eaten during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "beef carpaccio": "Pregnant women should not eat beef carpaccio. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook beef to at least 145&deg;F with a 3-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked beef. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "alfredo sauce": "Alfredo Sauce, if made with pastreurized ingredients, is safe to eat in moderation during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/513787-the-safety-of-alfredo-sauce-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. However,&nbsp;Alfredo Sauce made with unpasteurized butter or other dairy products is not safe for pregnant women to eat, according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Unpasteurized dairy products&nbsp;may contain bacteria such as Listeria, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby. #@:", "austrian smoked cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Austrian Smoked Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "ground turkey": "Pregnant women can enjoy ground turkey if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook ground turkey to at least 165&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked turkey. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "sea urchin (uni)": "Pregnant women can enjoy sea urchin (also known as uni) as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;sea urchin is in the class of seafood considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat sea urchin if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "tiramisu": "Tiramisu made with pasteurized eggs is safe to eat. However, according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>,&nbsp;some Tiramisu is made with unpasteurized eggs and should be avoided while pregnant.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\">BabyMed </a>and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a> state that raw eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby.&nbsp; Tiramisu may also contain alcohol and there is no safe amount of alcohol during pregnancy. However, tiramisu made with pasteurized eggs and without alcohol is safe for pregnant women to ingest.#@:", "kobe beef (wagyu beef)": "Pregnant women can enjoy kobe beef (also known as wagyu beef) if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook beef to at least 145&deg;F with a 3-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked beef. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/544993-what-are-the-health-benefits-of-red-meat-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a> states that lean beef has a lot of health benefits for pregnant women. #@:", "panela cheese": "Non-imported Panela Cheese made with pasteurized milk is considered safe for pregnant women according to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm106913.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>.&nbsp;However, pregnant women should avoid Panela Cheese made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "pecorino romano cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Pecorino Romano Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;#@:", "bologna": "Pregnant women can eat deli meats, such as bologna, if they are reheated until steaming hot or 165&deg;F and if they do not contain nitrates or nitrites, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/372099-can-pregnant-women-eat-deli-meat/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, the <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/features/pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">CDC</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>. According to the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, deli meats such as bologna may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. Listeria grows on meat at refrigirator temperatures.&nbsp;#@:", "cacioccvallo cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, soft and processed cheese such as Cacioccvallo Cheese is considered safe for pregnant women because it is generally made with pasteurized milk or is cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is pasteurized or is made with pasteurized milk.#@:", "spicy food": "Eating spicy food is considered safe during pregnancy. However, eating spicy food may cause discomfort during digestion for some pregnant women according to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/406_is-it-safe-to-eat-really-spicy-foods-during-pregnancy_1246919.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>.#@:", "hot dogs": "Pregnant women can eat hot dogs if they are heated until steaming hot or 165&deg;F, according to the <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/features/pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">CDC</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>. According to the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, hot dogs may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. Listeria grows on meat at refrigirator temperatures.&nbsp;#@:", "red wine": "Pregnant women should not drink red wine. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, there is no amount of alcohol that is considered safe during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "barley beans": "Barley beans are a safe choice during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.pregnancyandbaby.com/pregnancy/articles/945615/10-foods-every-pregnant-woman-should-eat\" target=\"_blank\">Pregnancy and Baby</a>.#@:", "boursin cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113896-boursin-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, soft and processed cheese such as Boursin Cheese is considered safe for pregnant women because it is generally made with pasteurized milk or is cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is pasteurized or is made with pasteurized milk.#@:", "ahi tuna": "Pregnant women should not eat ahi tuna. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;ahi tuna is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "dried strawberries": "Dried strawberries are considered safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "quark cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, soft and processed cheese such as Quark Cheese is considered safe for pregnant women because it is generally made with pasteurized milk or is cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is pasteurized or is made with pasteurized milk.#@:", "salami": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/salami-during-pregnancy-is-it-safe-to-eat\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Med</a>, pregnant women should not eat salami.#@:", "dried figs": "Dried figs are considered safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "pancetta": "Pregnant women can enjoy pancetta, or Italian bacon, if it is fully cooked and does not contain nitrates or nitrites. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook pork to at least 160&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked bacon. <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/513685-bacon-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong </a>states that bacon should be cooked until it is crispy and red in color and should be inspected for any spots where it was not cooked all the way through.&nbsp;#@:", "camembert cheese": "Non-imported Camembert made with pasteurized milk is considered safe for pregnant women according to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. However, pregnant women should avoid&nbsp;Camembert made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "ranch dressing": "Ranch dressing is safe to eat during pregnancy. <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/495683-what-salad-dressings-can-a-pregnant-woman-have/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a> recommends choosing low-fat ranch as a healthier option during pregnancy.#@:", "macaroni and cheese": "Macaroni and cheese is safe to eat during pregnancy if it is made with pasteurized or pregnancy-safe cheese. Pregnant women should confirm that they can eat the cheese in the macaroni and cheese by searching for it in the search window above.#@:", "shrimp": "Pregnant women can enjoy shrimp as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;shrimp is in the class of seafood considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat shrimp if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F. Shrimp should be cooked until it turns red and the meat is pearly opaque. #@:", "pretzels": "Pretzels are a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/117401-foods-nausea-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Pretzels are known to help with nausea during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "prune juice": "Prune juice is safe during pregnancy if it is pasteurized. Prunes contain high amounts of Potassium, which according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/556102-a-natural-food-good-for-swelling-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, helps remedy swelling and constipation during pregnancy.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> writes that fresh-squeezed juice may not always be pasteurized, which means that harmful bacteria like Salmonella and E. Coli may be present in the juice.&nbsp;Pregnant women should avoid fresh juice without a label stating that it is pasteurized.#@:", "fish carpaccio": "Pregnant women should not eat fish carpaccio. Fish carpaccio is usually made with raw or undercooked fish. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F. &nbsp;#@:", "chili peppers": "Chili peppers are a safe choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their chili peppers prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "asiago cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Asiago Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures.&nbsp;To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk.#@:", "vodka sauce": "Vodka sauce is usually served with pasta and contains unknown amounts of vodka (alcohol). <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/550869-is-vodka-sauce-safe-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a> recommends avoiding vodka sauce during pregnancy.#@:", "tilefish": "Pregnant women should not eat tilefish. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;tilefish is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "peanut butter": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.marchofdimes.com/pregnancy/nutrition_peanut.html\" target=\"_blank\">March of Dimes</a>, pregnant women who are not allergic to peanuts can safely eat peanut butter.&nbsp;#@:", "raw milk": "Raw milk, which is unpasteurized, is generally considered unsafe during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "champagne": "Pregnant women should not drink champagne. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, there is no amount of alcohol that is considered safe during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "bergader cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Bergader Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a>&nbsp;Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "sablefish": "Pregnant women can enjoy sablefish as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Sablefish is in the class of fish considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat sablefish if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "babybel cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Babybel Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "danish blue cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Danish Blue Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>. Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "prosciutto": "Pregnant women can eat deli meats, such as prossciutto, if they are reheated until steaming hot or 165&deg;F and if they do not contain nitrates or nitrites, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/182925-prosciutto-and-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, the <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/features/pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">CDC</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>. According to the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, deli meats may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. Listeria grows on meat at refrigirator temperatures.&nbsp;#@:", "cream cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">t</a>he <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/listeria.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, cream cheeese is considered safe for pregnant women if it is pasteurized or is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;#@:", "marlin": "Pregnant women should not eat marlin. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;marlin is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "rice": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/news/20111204/eating-rice-may-raise-arsenic-levels\" target=\"_blank\">WebMd</a>, a new&nbsp;study has shown high and potentially toxic levels of arsenic in pregnant women who recently ate rice. This study did not address whether this exposure is a health threat to the pregnant woman or her baby. Pregnant women should consult their physicians prior to consuming rice. #@:", "fromage frais": "<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.in/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a> writes that Fromage Frais is safe to eat while pregnant as long as it is made with pasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may contain a very harmful bacteria called Listeria according to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>. The <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a> writes that listeria can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.&nbsp;#@:", "black-eyed peas": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/272099-black-eyed-peas-nutrition/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, cooked black-eyed peas are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "deli meats": "Pregnant women can eat deli meats if they are reheated until steaming hot or 165&deg;F and if they do not contain nitrates or nitrites, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/372099-can-pregnant-women-eat-deli-meat/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, the <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/features/pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">CDC</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>. According to the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, deli meats may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. Listeria grows on meat at refrigirator temperatures.&nbsp;#@:", "mangos": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, mangos are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their mangos prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.&nbsp;#@:", "apple juice": "Apple juice is safe during pregnancy if it is pasteurized, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/491340-is-it-okay-to-drink-diluted-apple-juice-during-early-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> states that fresh-squeezed juice may not always be pasteurized, which means that harmful bacteria like Salmonella and E. Coli may be present in the juice. Pregnant women should avoid fresh juice without a label stating that it is pasteurized.&nbsp;#@:", "hot sauce": "Eating food that contains hot sauce is considered safe during pregnancy. However, eating spicy foods may cause discomfort during digestion for some pregnant women according to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/406_is-it-safe-to-eat-really-spicy-foods-during-pregnancy_1246919.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>.#@:", "jarlsberg cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Jarlsberg Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "mozzarella cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/491761-is-mozzarella-cheese-okay-for-pregnant-women-to-eat/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, Mozarella Cheese is considered safe for pregnant women if it is pasteurized or is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;#@:", "pineapple": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, pineapples are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their pineapples prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "cheeseburgers": "Pregnant women can enjoy cheeseburgers (beef) if they are fully and properly cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook ground beef to at least 160&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked beef. According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/513885-is-it-safe-to-eat-hamburgers-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, undercooked or spoiled burger patties may contain food-borne bacteria such as Listeria, which can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.&nbsp;#@:", "whiting": "Pregnant women can enjoy whiting as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;whiting is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat whiting if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "chocolate": "There have been many opposing studies on the safety of caffiene intake during pregnancy. Because of the uncertainty about caffeine\'s risk of miscarriage and premature birth, <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> reccomends that foods with caffeine like coffee, some teas, and energy drinks be avoided or limited to 200mg per day during pregnancy. Out of an abundance of caution, pregnant mommies should limit chocolate during pregnancy accordingly.#@:", "queso blanco cheese": "Non-imported Queso Blanco made with pasteurized milk is considered safe for pregnant women according to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm106913.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>.&nbsp;However, pregnant women should avoid&nbsp;Queso Blanco made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "cassava": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/510228-can-pregnant-women-eat-root-vegetables/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, cassava is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their cassava prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "oat bran muffins": "Oat Bran Muffins are a safe choice during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. Oat Bran Muffins are high in fiber and can relieve constipation if eaten during pregnancy.#@:", "jicama": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/349069-salads-safe-eat-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, jicama is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their jicama prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "quesadillas": "Quesadillas are considered safe for pregnant women if they are made with a safe cheese and if the meat in them is properly cooked.#@:", "canned tuna (light)": "Pregnant women can enjoy canned chunk light tuna (fully cooked)&nbsp;as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;canned chuck light tuna is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "pont l›eveque cheese": "Soft cheeses such as Pont L\'Eveque Cheese are generally considered unsafe for pregnant women according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a> &nbsp;Soft cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "provolone cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Provolone Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "popcorn": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_the-ten-best-foods-for-pregnancy_10320506.bc#articlesection5\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter</a>, popcorn is not only a safe but a healthy option for pregnant women. However, it is best to avoid microwave popcorn bags that contain the toxin&nbsp;Fluorotelomers in the lining due to conflicting studies about its safety.&nbsp;#@:", "vacherin-fribourgeois cheese": "Soft cheeses such as Vacherin-Fribourgeois Cheese are generally considered unsafe for pregnant women according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a> &nbsp;Soft cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "unpasteurized cheese": "Unpasteurized cheese, made with unpasteurized milk, is generally considered unsafe during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "spaghetti squash": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/516976-are-zucchini-squash-ok-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, spaghetti squash is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their squash prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "toro": "Pregnant women should not eat toro (also known as bigeye, bluefin, and yellofin tuna). Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/sushimercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, toro is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "yohimbe": "Yohimbe is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "smoked seafood": "Pregnant women should not eat smoked seafood. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, smoked seafood could contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.&nbsp;#@:", "derby cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Derby Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "halloumi cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Halloumi Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "goat cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>, Goat Cheese without white rind is safe for pregnant women to eat.&nbsp;However, pregnant women should avoid Goat Cheese made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "cascara sagrada": "Cascara Sagrada is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "sour creme": "<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.in/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a> states that sour cream is safe to eat while pregnant if it is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "nectarines": "According to <a href=\"http://www.eatright.org/Public/content.aspx?id=6808\" target=\"_blank\">Eatright.org</a>, nectarines are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their nectarines prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "ground lamb": "Pregnant women can enjoy ground lamb if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook ground lamb to at least 160&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked lamb.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "diet coke": "Generally, pregnant women can drink Diet Coke, which contains caffeine, in moderation. There have been many opposing studies regarding the safety of caffeine intake during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;caffeine is permitted during pregnancy but intake should be limited to under 200mg per day. However, some sources suggest to avoid all caffeinated products during the first trimester of pregnancy. Diet Coke contains the artificial sweetner aspartame, which&nbsp;should not be ingested by pregnant women with PKU (a rare metabolic disorder), rare liver disease, or by pregnant women who have high levels of phenylalanine in their blood according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "alcohol": "Pregnant women should not drink alcohol. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, there is no amount of alcohol that is considered safe during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "gin": "Pregnant women should not drink gin. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, there is no amount of alcohol that is considered safe during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "kidney beans": "Kidney beans are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/guide/eating-right-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "veal": "Pregnant women can enjoy veal if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook veal to at least 145&deg;F with a 3-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked veal.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "soda (caffeinated)": "There have been many opposing studies regarding the safety of caffeine intake during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;caffeine is permitted during pregnancy but intake should be limited to under 200mg per day. However, some sources suggest to avoid all caffeinated products during the first trimester of pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "lima beans": "Lima beans are a safe and healthy option during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/guide/eating-right-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>. Lima beans are high in folic acid, which is essential during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "english goat›s cheddar cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as English Goat\'s Cheddar Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "cheshire cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Cheshire Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "radish sprouts (raw)": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>, any type of raw sprouts should be avoided while pregnant because bacteria may enter into the seeds before the sprouts grow. Washing sprouts does not get rid of the bacteria. Raw sprouts to avoid include alfalfa, clover, and radish sprouts.#@:", "lobster": "Pregnant women can enjoy lobster as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Lobster is in the class of seafood considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat lobster if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F. Lobster should be cooked until it turns red and the meat is pearly opaque.&nbsp;#@:", "artificial sweeteners": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, the FDA considers the following artificial sweeteners safe to ingest in moderation during pregnancy: Rebaudioside A (Stevia),&nbsp;Acesulfame Potassium (Sunett), Sucralose (Splenda) and Aspartame (Equal or NutraSweet). However, Aspartame (Equal or NutraSweet) should not be ingested by pregnant women with PKU (a rare metabolic disorder), rare liver disease, or by pregnant women who have high levels of phenylalanine in their blood. The <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a> advises to avoid artificial sweeteners containing saccharin (Sweet\'N Low) and cyclamate.#@:", "herring": "Pregnant women can enjoy herring as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;herring is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat herring if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "golden seal": "Golden Seal is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "tilapia": "Pregnant women can enjoy tilapia as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;tilapia is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat tilapia if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "wormwood": "Wormwood is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "feta cheese": "Non-imported Feta Cheese made with pasteurized milk is considered safe for pregnant women according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/284414-how-to-eat-feta-cheese-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a> and the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. However, pregnant women should avoid Feta Cheese made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "anchovies": "Pregnant women can enjoy anchovies as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;anchovies are in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat anchovies if they are fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "queso fresco cheese": "Non-imported Queso Fresco made with pasteurized milk is considered safe for pregnant women according to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. However, pregnant women should avoid&nbsp;Queso Fresco made from unpasteurized milk. Unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "chili powder": "Eating food that contains chili powder is considered safe during pregnancy. However, eating spicy foods may cause discomfort during digestion for some pregnant women according to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/406_is-it-safe-to-eat-really-spicy-foods-during-pregnancy_1246919.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>.#@:", "meat spreads": "Pregnant women should not eat meat spreads according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a> and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/can-you-have-pate-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "striped bass": "Pregnant women can enjoy striped bass as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Striped bass is in the class of fish considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat striped bass if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "bluefin tuna": "Pregnant women should not eat bluefin tuna. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women eat to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/sushimercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;bluefin tuna is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "eggs": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, eggs are a safe choice for pregnant women if they are cooked until both the yolks and the whites are firm. Recipes with eggs, such as quiches, should be cooked to&nbsp;160 &deg;F.#@:", "lettuce": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/516612-is-lettuce-good-while-you-are-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, lettuce is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their lettuce prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "watermelon": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, watermelon is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their watermelon prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "lancashire cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Lancashire Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk.#@:", "cranberry juice": "Cranberry juice is safe during pregnancy if it is pasteurized, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/491340-is-it-okay-to-drink-diluted-apple-juice-during-early-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> states that fresh-squeezed juice may not always be pasteurized, which means that harmful bacteria like Salmonella and E. Coli may be present in the juice. Pregnant women should avoid fresh juice without a label stating that it is pasteurized.&nbsp;#@:", "dried cherries": "Dried cherries are considered safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "manchego cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Machego Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;#@:", "orange juice": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/508636-is-it-unhealthy-to-drink-orange-juice-while-pregnant/\">Livestrong</a> and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/is-it-safe-to-have-fruit-juice-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>, orange juice is not only a safe choice but is also a healthy choice for a pregnant woman. <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> writes that fresh-squeezed juice may not always be pasteurized, which means that harmful bacteria like Salmonella and E. Coli may be present in the juice.&nbsp;Pregnant women should avoid fresh juice without a label stating that it is pasteurized.#@:", "peaches": "According to <a href=\"http://www.eatright.org/Public/content.aspx?id=6808\" target=\"_blank\">Eatright.org</a>, peaches are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy.&nbsp;However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their peaches prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "shad": "Pregnant women can enjoy shad (American) as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;shad is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat shad if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "7up": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/327660-can-pregnant-women-drink-diet-soda/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, 7Up does not contain caffeine and is safe to drink in moderation during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "splenda (sucralose)": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, the FDA considers Splenda (Sucralose) safe in moderation during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "orkney cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Orkney Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;#@:", "cucumbers": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_10-fast-foods-a-pregnant-woman-could-love-and-five-to-avoid_1313899.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>, cucumbers are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their cucumbers prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "sriracha sauce": "Sriracha is a spicy sauce used in Japanese food. Eating spicy foods while pregnant is considered safe, but can cause discomfort during digestion according to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/406_is-it-safe-to-eat-really-spicy-foods-during-pregnancy_1246919.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>.#@:", "sesame seeds": "Sesame seeds are a safe choice during pregnancy according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/476934-why-should-you-avoid-sesame-seeds-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>. However, pregnant women should consult their physician prior to eating sesame seeds because some physicians may recommend avoiding sesame seeds in the first trimester of pregnancy. #@:", "broccoli": "According to <a href=\"http://www.parents.com/pregnancy/my-body/nutrition/5-great-pregnancy-foods/?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">Parents.com</a>, broccoli is one of the five essential foods to eat during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their broccoli prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "ground pork": "Pregnant women can enjoy ground pork if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook ground beef to at least 160&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked pork. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "liver": "Pregnant women should not consume liver according to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/it-safe-eat-liver-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.marchofdimes.com/pregnancy/nutrition_risks.html\" target=\"_blank\">March of Dimes</a>. Some studies have shown that the high amounts of vitamin A in liver may cause birth defects.&nbsp;#@:", "mussels": "Pregnant women can enjoy mussels in limited amounts if they are fully cooked, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/332318-can-i-eat-mussels-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat mussels if they are fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook mussels until the shells open. If the shells do not open, those mussels should not be eaten. #@:", "yellowfin tuna": "Pregnant women should not eat yellowfin tuna. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women eat to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/sushimercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;yellowfin tuna is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "delicata squash": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/516976-are-zucchini-squash-ok-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, squash is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their squash prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "skate": "Pregnant women can enjoy skate as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Skate is in the class of fish considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat skate if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "turnips": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/guide/eating-right-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/429239-nutrition-in-mustard-turnip-collard-greens/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, turnips are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it essential that pregnant women wash their turnips prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "chives": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/vitamins-supplements/ingredientmono-403-CHIVE.aspx?activeIngredientId=403&amp;activeIngredientName=CHIVE\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>, chives are a safe choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their chives prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "ground veal": "Pregnant women can enjoy ground veal if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook ground veal to at least 160&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked veal. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "crab": "Pregnant women can enjoy crab as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;crab is in the class of seafood considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat crab if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F. Crab should be cooked until it turns red and the meat is pearly opaque.&nbsp;#@:", "bleu d›auvergne cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Bleu d\'Auvergne Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a>&nbsp;Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "lamb": "Pregnant women can enjoy lamb if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook lamb to at least 145&deg;F with a three-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked lamb.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "ketchup": "Ketchup is a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.pregnancyandbaby.com/pregnancy/articles/945817/picnic-foods-pregnant-women-should-avoid\" target=\"_blank\">Pregnancy and Baby</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "oranges": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.org</a>, oranges are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their oranges prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Even produce with skin, rinds or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.&nbsp;#@:", "tea": "There have been many opposing studies on the safety of caffiene intake during pregnancy. Because of the uncertainty about caffeine\'s connection to miscarriage and premature birth, <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> reccomends that drinks with caffeine be avoided or limited to 200mg per day during pregnancy. However, some sources suggest to avoid all caffeinated products during the first trimester of pregnancy.#@:", "beef": "Pregnant women can enjoy beef if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook beef to at least 145&deg;F with a 3-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked beef. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.&nbsp;#@:", "citrum aurantium": "Citrum Aurantium is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "broccoli rabe": "Broccoli rabe is safe to eat during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their broccoli rabe prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "creme fraiche": "<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.in/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a> states that Creme Fraiche is safe to eat while pregnant if it is made with pasteurized milk.&nbsp;According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "hot peppers": "Although safe to eat during pregnancy, hot peppers may cause heartburn, rectal discomfort, and overall discomfort to pregnancy women according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/342380-hot-pepper-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. It is essential that pregnant women wash their peppers prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "octopus (tako)": "Pregnant women can enjoy octopus (also known as tako) as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;octopus is in the class of seafood considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat octopus if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "walnuts": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_the-ten-best-foods-for-pregnancy_10320506.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>, walnuts are a safe choice during pregnancy.#@:", "winter squash": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/516976-are-zucchini-squash-ok-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, winter squash is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their squash prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "haddock": "Pregnant women can enjoy haddock as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;haddock is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat haddock if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "bocconcini cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>, Bocconcini Cheese is considered safe for pregnant women if it is bought pre-packaged and is pasteurized.&nbsp;#@:", "betel": "Betel is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "mullet": "Pregnant women can enjoy mullet as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;mullet is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat mullet if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "eggnog": "Eggnog made with cooked pasteurized eggs, as opposed to raw or unpasteurized eggs, is safe to drink during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-drink-eggnog-during-pregnancy_10322.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter</a>.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\">BabyMed </a>and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a> state that raw eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby. #@:", "stevia (rebaudioside a)": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, the FDA considers Stevia (Rebaudioside A) safe in moderation during pregnancy. However, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/423285-stevia-and-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, there have been limited studies done on the safety of Stevia during pregnancy in humans.&nbsp;#@:", "almonds": "Almonds are a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. They are high in fiber and can relieve constipation.&nbsp;#@:", "pumpkins": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/pumpkin-during-pregnancy-it-safe\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>, pumpkins are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy.&nbsp;However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their pumpkins prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "bok choy": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/356577-what-are-the-health-benefits-of-bok-choy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, bok choy is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their bok choy prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "masago (smelt egg)": "Pregnant women can enjoy masago (also known as smelt egg) as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;masago is in the class of seafood considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat smelt egg if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "sweet potatoes": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_the-ten-best-foods-for-pregnancy_10320506.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>, sweet potatoes are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their potatoes before eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "mushrooms": "According to <a href=\"http://Some, mushrooms are poisonous to eat so make sure you are buying mushrooms from safe manufacturers to keep your baby safe!&lt;/p\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, mushrooms are a safe choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their mushorooms prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "blue cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Blue Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a>&nbsp;Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "cabbage": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/481041-can-you-eat-cabbage-when-youre-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, cabbage is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their cabbage well prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "kale": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/349069-salads-safe-eat-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, kale is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their kale prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "blue wensleydale cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Blue Wensleydale Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a>&nbsp;Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "pomegranate juice": "Although pomegranate juice is generally considered safe during pregnancy if it is pasteurized, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/312065-healthy-fruit-juices-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, it may interact negatively with some medications. Pregnant women should consult with their doctor prior to drinking pomegranate juice about this. &nbsp;Also pregnant women with gestational diabetes should also consult with their doctor about the safety of pomegranate juice in their diet.#@:", "caerphilly cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Caerphilly Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "roquefort cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Roquefort Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>. Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "pears": "According to <a href=\"http://www.eatright.org/Public/content.aspx?id=6808\" target=\"_blank\">Eatright.org</a>, pears are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their pears prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "cheddar cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Cheddar Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk.#@:", "pumpkin seeds": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/555460-do-pumpkin-seeds-affect-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, pumpkin seeds are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "emmental cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Emmental Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "raspberries": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, raspberries are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their raspberries prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "dried fruit": "Dried fruit is safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "oat bran": "Oat Bran is a safe choice during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "foie gras (fat liver)": "Pregnant women should not eat fois gras, duck or goose fat liver, according to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/can-you-have-pate-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed </a>and<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/553322-is-seared-foie-gras-safe-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">&nbsp;Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "spelt": "Spelt is a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/118247-foods-can-eat-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a> and <a href=\"http://www.pregnancyandbaby.com/pregnancy/articles/945615/10-foods-every-pregnant-woman-should-eat\" target=\"_blank\">Pregnancy and Baby</a>. Spelt is high in fiber and can relieve constipation if eaten during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "turkey": "Pregnant women can enjoy turkey if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook turkey to at least 165&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked turkey.&nbsp;Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "raw-milk cheese": "Raw-milk cheese, made with unpasteurized milk is generally considered unsafe during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.&nbsp;#@:", "oat groats": "Oat Groats are a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. Oat Groats are high in fiber and can relieve constipation if eaten during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "carrots": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/carrots-and-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/nutrientsvitaminspregnancy.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, carrots are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their carrots prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "edam cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Edam Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "honeydew melon": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/guide/eating-right-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>, honeydew melon is a safe and healthy option during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their melon prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "black bass": "Pregnant women can enjoy black bass as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Black Bass is in the class of fish that is considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat black bass if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "mayonnaise": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\">WebMd</a>,&nbsp;mayonnaise made with raw eggs, often found in restaurants, is not safe for pregnant women to eat.&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\">BabyMed </a>and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a> state that raw eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby.&nbsp; However, mayonnaise made with pasteurized eggs is safe for pregnant women to ingest.#@:", "scallions": "Scallions are a safe choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their scallions prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "yogurt": "Yogurt made with pasteurized milk is safe for pregnant women. However, yogurt made with unpasteurized milk is considered unsafe during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "fennel": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/467144-eating-fennel-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, fennel is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their fennel prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "fanta": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/327660-can-pregnant-women-drink-diet-soda/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, Fanta does not contain caffeine and is safe to drink in moderation during pregnancy. Fanta contains&nbsp;Aspartame, which is ok only in moderation according to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/406_is-it-safe-to-drink-diet-soda-during-pregnancy_1245945.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter</a>.&nbsp;However, Aspartame should not be ingested by pregnant women with PKU (a rare metabolic disorder), rare liver disease, or by pregnant women who have high levels of phenylalanine in their blood according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.#@:", "grouper": "Pregnant women can enjoy grouper as part of the three six-ounce servings of high mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Grouper is in the class of fish considered to have a high amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat grouper if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145 &deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "tap water": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=2\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>, tap water that flows through lead pipes should be avoided during pregnancy because lead is known to cause problems during birth and development delays in babies. Filtered water is recommended for pregnant women.#@:", "collard greens": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/429239-nutrition-in-mustard-turnip-collard-greens/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong,</a> collard greens are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their collard greens prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "garcinai cambogia": "Garcinai Cambogia is unsafe to eat during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "double gloucester cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Double Gloucester Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "chabichou cheese": "Soft cheeses such as Chabichou Cheese are generally considered unsafe for pregnant women according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a> &nbsp;Soft cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "bearnaise sauce": "Bearnaise sauce made with raw eggs is not safe for pregnant women to eat according to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMd.</a>&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a> state that raw eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby. However, bearnaise sauce made with pasteurized eggs is safe for pregnant women to eat.&nbsp;#@:", "plums": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, plums are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their plums prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "guava": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, guavas are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their guavas prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "raw shellfish": "Pregnant women should not eat raw shellfish. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should avoid eating raw or undercooked shellfish. #@:", "molasses": "According to <a href=\"http://www.fitpregnancy.com/nutrition-recipes/prenatal-nutrition/10-surprising-prenatal-power-foods?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">Fit Pregnancy</a>, molasses is a safe choice during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "oilfish": "Pregnant women should not eat oilfish because it may contain indigestible wax ester that causes digestion problems and diarrhea according to <a href=\"http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/content/cda-pubs-cdi-2002-cdi2603-htm-cdi2603i.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Health.gov.au</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "blueberries": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, blueberries are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their blueberries prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "garbanzo beans": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/552323-garbanzo-beans-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, garbanzo beans are a safe and healthy option for pregnant women. However, if they are left out at room temperature for more than two hours after being cooked they need to be discarded due to possible bacteria growth.#@:", "bigeye tuna": "Pregnant women should not eat bigeye tuna. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;bigeye tuna is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "kiwis": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, kiwis are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their kiwis prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "perch": "Pregnant women can enjoy perch as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;perch is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat perch if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "parsley": "Parsley is a safe choice during pregnancy. Parsley is a diuretic food, which according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/556102-a-natural-food-good-for-swelling-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, helps remedy edema during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their parsley prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "acorn squash": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/516976-are-zucchini-squash-ok-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, squash is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their squash prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "spinach": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/308733-list-of-healthy-foods-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, spinach is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their spinach prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "avocados": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/308733-list-of-healthy-foods-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, avocado is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their avocado prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "dried mangos": "Dried Mangos are considered safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "cherries": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, cherries are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their cherries prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "ham": "Pregnant women can eat ham if it is properly cooked or reheated.&nbsp;According to the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, deli meat like ham may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. Listeria grows on meat at refrigirator temperatures. According the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, fully cooked ham packaged at a USDA-inspected plant should be heated to 140&deg;F, fully cooked ham packaged at another location should be heated to&nbsp;165&deg;F, and leftover ham should be reheated to&nbsp;165&deg;F.#@:", "crawfish (crayfish)": "Pregnant women can enjoy crawfish (also known as crayfish) as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;crawfish is in the class of seafood considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat crawfish if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F. Crawfish should be cooked until it is red and the meat is pearly opaque.&nbsp;#@:", "celery": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/493612-is-celery-bad-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, celery is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their celery prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "aspartame (equal or nutrasweet)": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, the FDA considers Aspartame (Equal or NutraSweet) safe in moderation during pregnancy.#@:", "leeks": "According to <a href=\"http://www.fitpregnancy.com/nutrition-recipes/prenatal-nutrition/10-surprising-prenatal-power-foods?page=2\" target=\"_blank\">Fit Pregnancy</a>, leeks are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their leeks prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "roncal cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Roncal Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>. Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "dried pineapples": "Dried pineapples are considered safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "ground beef": "Pregnant women can enjoy ground beef if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook ground beef to at least 160&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked beef. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/544993-what-are-the-health-benefits-of-red-meat-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a> states that lean beef has a lot of health benefits for pregnant women. #@:", "rutabaga": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/510228-can-pregnant-women-eat-root-vegetables/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, rutabaga is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their rutabaga prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "taleggio cheese": "Soft cheeses such as Taleggio Cheese are generally considered unsafe for pregnant women according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a> &nbsp;Soft cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "pizza": "Pizza is safe to eat during pregnancy. However, greasy pizza with a lot of cheese and meat on top contains a high amount of fat and should only be eaten occasionally according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/315585-is-pizza-healthy-for-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. Pregnant women should opt for healthier alternatives, with whole grain dough and vegetables.#@:", "hake": "Pregnant women can enjoy hake as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, hake is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat hake if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "grapes": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, grapes are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their grapes prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "daikon radish": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/503658-can-pregnant-women-eat-radishes/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, radishes are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their radishes prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "mustard": "Mustard is a safe option during pregnancy.#@:", "kingfish": "Pregnant women should not eat kingfish. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/269350-kingfish-nutrition-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>,&nbsp;kingfish is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "orange roughy": "Pregnant women should not eat orange roughy. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;orange roughy is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "pistachios": "Pistachios are a safe choice during pregnancy. Pistachios are high in fiber and can relieve constipation if eaten during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "swiss cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Swiss Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "dates": "Dates are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their dates prior to eating them.&nbsp;Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "herbal tea": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>, herbal teas, although often caffeine-free, are not necessarily safe. Consult your healthcare provider before drinking herbal tea.#@:", "marinara sauce": "Marinara sauce is safe to eat during prengnancy. However, Marinara sauce can be acidic and may cause heartburn and discomfort during digestion during pregnancy according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/538260-nutritional-value-of-tomatoes-for-pregnancy/\"> Baby Center</a>.#@:", "coke (coca cola)": "Pregnant women can drink Coke (coca-cola), which contains caffeine, in moderation. There have been many opposing studies regarding the safety of caffeine intake during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;caffeine is permitted during pregnancy but intake should be limited to under 200mg per day. However, some sources suggest to avoid all caffeinated products during the first trimester of pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "beer": "Pregnant women should not drink beer. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, there is no amount of alcohol that is considered safe during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "split peas": "Split peas are a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/274078-pregnant-foods-to-avoid-constipation/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "chlorella": "Chlorella (a blue-green algae) is a safe choice during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/282451-a-list-of-vegan-super-foods-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. Chlorella is known to prevent anemia, proteinuria and edema in pregnancies.#@:", "butternut squash": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/516976-are-zucchini-squash-ok-for-pregnant-women/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, butternut squash is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their squash prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "monterrey jack cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Monterrey Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk.#@:", "sprite": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/327660-can-pregnant-women-drink-diet-soda/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, Sprite does not contain caffeine and is safe to drink in moderation during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "green peas": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/289167-proper-nutrition-during-pregnancy-for-a-healthy-baby/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, green peas are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their peas prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "tequila": "Pregnant women should not drink tequila. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, there is no amount of alcohol that is considered safe during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "mug root beer": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/327660-can-pregnant-women-drink-diet-soda/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, Mug Root Beer does not contain caffeine and is safe to drink in moderation during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "unpasteurized milk": "Unpasteurized milk is generally considered unsafe during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby.#@:", "chia seeds": "Chia Seeds can be safely eaten during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/486314-can-pregnant-women-eat-chia-seeds/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. However, pregnant women should check with their physicians prior to consuming chia seeds as a dietary supplement.&nbsp;#@:", "diet soda": "The safety of drinking diet soda while pregnant depends on the artificial sweeteners in the diet soda and whether or not it is caffeinated. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, the FDA considers the following artificial sweeteners safe to ingest in moderation during pregnancy: Rebaudioside A (Stevia),&nbsp;Acesulfame Potassium (Sunett), Sucralose (Splenda) and Aspartame (Equal or NutraSweet). However, Aspartame (Equal or NutraSweet) should not be ingested by pregnant women with PKU (a rare metabolic disorder), rare liver disease, or by pregnant women who have high levels of phenylalanine in their blood. The <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/artificialsweetner.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a> advises to avoid artificial sweeteners containing saccharin (Sweet n\'Low) and cyclamate.#@:", "soppressata": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/salami-during-pregnancy-is-it-safe-to-eat\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Med</a>, pregnant women should avoid soppressata (Italian dry salami).#@:", "carp": "Pregnant women can enjoy carp as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Carp is in the class of fish considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat carp if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "pao d›arco": "Pao D\'Arco is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "alfalfa sprouts (raw)": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>, any type of raw sprouts should be avoided while pregnant because bacteria may enter into the seeds before the sprouts grow. Washing sprouts does not get rid of the bacteria. Raw sprouts to avoid include alfalfa, clover, and radish sprouts.#@:", "eel (unagi)": "Pregnant women can enjoy Eel (also known as unagi) as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;eel is in the class of seafood considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat eel if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "basil": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/466216-can-i-eat-basil-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, basil is a safe choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their basil prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "tomatoes": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/538260-nutritional-value-of-tomatoes-for-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, tomatoes are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their tomatoes prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "yams": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/528240-can-pregnant-women-eat-yams/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, yams are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their yams prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "swordfish": "Pregnant women should not eat swordfish. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;swordfish is in the class of fish considered to have the highest amount of mercury.&nbsp;#@:", "dried cranberries (craisins)": "Dried cranberries (craisins) are considered safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "melons": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/pregnancynutrition.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, melons are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their melons prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "turkey burger": "Pregnant women can enjoy turkey burgers if they are properly cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook ground turkey to at least 165&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked turkey. According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/513885-is-it-safe-to-eat-hamburgers-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, undercooked or spoiled burger patties may contain food-borne bacteria such as Listeria, which can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies, and E. Coli.&nbsp;#@:", "gatorade": "Gatorade is a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/tc/pregnancy-related-problems-home-treatment\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "limes": "Limes are safe to eat during pregnancy. However, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/262204-foods-to-avoid-in-pregnancy-with-indigestion/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, the high acidity in limes may cause indigestion and eat away the enamel of teeth during pregnancy. It is essential that pregnant women wash their limes prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "bananas": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, bananas are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy.&nbsp;However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their bananas prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "hamburgers": "Pregnant women can enjoy hamburgers (beef) if they are fully and properly cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook ground beef to at least 160&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked beef. According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/513885-is-it-safe-to-eat-hamburgers-while-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, undercooked or spoiled burger patties may contain food-borne bacteria such as Listeria, which can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies, and E. Coli.&nbsp;#@:", "raw eggs": "Raw eggs and food made with raw eggs should be avoided during pregnancy. According to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\">BabyMed </a>and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, raw eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby.#@:", "unwashed vegetables": "Pregnant women should not eat unwashed produce. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "corn": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.in/pregnancy/nutrition/eatingwell/09-12weeks/\" target=\"_blank\">babycenter</a>, corn is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. It is essential that pregnant women wash their corn prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "steak tartare": "Pregnant women should not eat steak tartare. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook beef to at least 145&deg;F with a 3-minute rest time and should not eat any raw or undercooked beef. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "french fries": "French fries are safe for pregnant women to eat in moderaton. Because french fries are usually deep fried and are high in salt, carbohydrates, and fat, they are unhealthy if consumed regularly according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/514874-the-effects-of-french-fries-on-your-body/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "honey": "Honey is safe during pregnancy if it is pasteurized, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/327947-foods-to-avoid-during-pregnancy-honey/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-honey-during-pregnancy_10305372.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;states that&nbsp;unpasteurized honey may contain bacteria, such as C. botulinum, which could be potentially harmful to pregnant women and their babies.&nbsp;#@:", "pennyroyal": "Pennyroyal is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "senna": "Senna is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "tansy": "Tansy is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "cambozola cheese": "Soft cheeses such as Cambozola Cheese are generally considered unsafe for pregnant women according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/404_is-it-safe-to-eat-soft-cheese-during-pregnancy_3175.bc\" target=\"_blank\">BabyCenter.</a>&nbsp;Soft cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "radicchio": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/349069-salads-safe-eat-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, radicchio is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their radicchio prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "black beans": "Black beans are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/guide/eating-right-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "pinto beans": "According to <a href=\"http://www.fitpregnancy.com/nutrition-recipes/prenatal-nutrition/10-surprising-prenatal-power-foods\" target=\"_blank\">Fit Pregnancy</a>, cooked pinto beans are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy.#@:", "figs": "According to <a href=\"http://www.fitpregnancy.com/nutrition-recipes/prenatal-nutrition/10-surprising-prenatal-power-foods\" target=\"_blank\">Fit Pregnancy</a>, figs are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their figs prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "hollandaise (sauce dressing)": "Hollandaise sauce or dressing made with raw eggs, often found in restaurants, is not safe for pregnant women to eat according to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\">WebMd</a>.&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\">BabyMed</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a> state that raw eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both the pregnant woman and her baby.&nbsp; However, store-bought versions made with pasteurized eggs are safe for pregnant women to ingest.#@:", "caesar dressing": "Caesar dressing made with raw eggs, often found in restaurants, is not safe for pregnant women to eat, according to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/ss/slideshow-what-not-to-eat-when-pregnant\">WebMd</a>.&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\">BabyMed </a>and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a> state that raw eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby.&nbsp; However, caesar dressing made with pasteurized eggs is safe for pregnant women to ingest.#@:", "dolcelatte cheese": "Blue-veined cheeses such as Dolcelatte Cheese are considered unsafe for pregnant women according to<a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/113904-blue-cheese-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\"> Livestrong</a>. Blue-veined cheeses are often made with unpasteurized milk and can contain bacteria that is considered dangerous to both pregnant women and their babies. According to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>, unpasteurized milk may&nbsp;contain Listeria, a bacteria that can cause miscarriage or can cross the placenta and cause a potentially life-threatening infection to the baby. #@:", "sushi": "Pregnant women can enjoy sushi if it is made with cooked seafood. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook seafood to at least 145&deg;F. Pregnant women should confirm that they can eat the seafood in the sushi by searching for the ingredients in the search window above. &nbsp;#@:", "chicken nuggets": "Pregnant women can enjoy chicken nuggets if they are fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook chicken to at least 165&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked chicken. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "corned beef": "Pregnant women can eat deli meats, such as corned beef, if they are reheated until steaming hot or 165&deg;F and if it does not contain nitrates or nitrites, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/135157-corned-beef-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, the <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/features/pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">CDC</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>. According to the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, deli meats may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. Listeria grows on meat at refrigirator temperatures.&nbsp;#@:", "liverwurst": "Pregnant women should not consume liver products such as liverwurst according to <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/it-safe-eat-liver-during-pregnancy\" target=\"_blank\">BabyMed</a>&nbsp;and the <a href=\"http://www.marchofdimes.com/pregnancy/nutrition_risks.html\" target=\"_blank\">March of Dimes</a>. Some studies have shown that the high amounts of vitamin A in liver may cause birth defects.&nbsp;#@:", "venison": "Pregnant women can enjoy venison if it is fully cooked, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/409308-can-you-eat-venison-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm083327.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should cook venison to at least 160&deg;F and should not eat any raw or undercooked venison. Undercooked meat could contain harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.#@:", "chilean sea bass": "Pregnant women can enjoy chilean sea bass as part of the three six-ounce servings of high mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;Chilean sea bass is in the class of fish considered to have a high amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat chilena sea bass if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145 &deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "lasagna": "Lasagna is considered safe for pregnant women if it is made with a safe cheese and if the meat in it is properly cooked.&nbsp;#@:", "red leicester cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Red Leicester Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "dried apples": "Dried apples are considered safe during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/263085-what-are-the-benefits-of-dried-fruit-in-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Women with allergies to sulfites should check labels carefully because sulfites are used as preservatives in some dried fruit.#@:", "cantaloupe": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, cantaloupe is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their cantaloupe prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;Even produce with skin, rind or peel should be washed because bacteria or parasites accumulated on the outside of the produce can be inadvertantely ingested after peeling or cutting it.#@:", "kippered seafood": "Pregnant women should not eat kippered seafood. According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, kippered seafood could contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies.&nbsp;#@:", "garlic": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/285924-the-benefits-of-garlic-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, garlic is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. Pregnant women should not eat too much garlic before, during, or after labor because it is known to cause excessive bleeding. It is essential that pregnant women wash their garlic prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "pepperoni": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/368879-the-effects-of-eating-pepperoni-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, pregnant women should not eat pepperoni.#@:", "vitamin water": "Some flavors of vitamin water contain caffeine.&nbsp;There have been many opposing studies regarding the safety of caffeine intake during pregnancy. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;caffeine is permitted during pregnancy but intake should be limited to under 200mg per day. However, some sources suggest to avoid all caffeinated products during the first trimester of pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "red clover": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/273252-precautions-of-red-clover-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, there is no amount of red clover that is safe for pregnant women to eat. Red clover has been shown to cause contractions and can potentially cause a miscarriage or preterm labor.&nbsp;#@:", "whitefish": "Pregnant women can enjoy whitefish as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>,&nbsp;whitefish is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat whitefish if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "quiches": "A quiche is safe to eat when its internal tempreature reaches 160&deg; F and if it is made with cheese considered safe for pregnant women. Refrigirated quiches should be eaten within the day that they are made and reheated until steaming hot.&nbsp;#@:", "cauliflower": "According to <a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/guide/eating-right-when-pregnant\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>, cauliflower is a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their cauliflower prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "crackers": "Crackers are a safe option during pregnancy according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/117401-foods-nausea-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>.&nbsp;Crackers are known to help with nausea during pregnancy.&nbsp;#@:", "pecorino cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Pecorino Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "pastrami": "Pregnant women can eat deli meat, such as pastrami, if it is reheated until steaming hot or 165&deg;F and if it does not contain nitrates or nitrites, according to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/368879-the-effects-of-eating-pepperoni-during-pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, the <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/features/pregnancy/\" target=\"_blank\">CDC</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/downloads/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/SelectedHealthTopics/UCM312787.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>. According to the <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/pregnancy-breastfeeding/baby-safe-from-listeriosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">USDA</a>, deli meat may contain Listeria, a harmful bacteria that can cause severe health complications for pregnant women and their babies. Listeria grows on meat at refrigirator temperatures.&nbsp;#@:", "black walnut": "Black Walnut is considered unsafe during pregnancy according to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.webmd.com/baby/features/foods-to-avoid-when-youre-pregnant?page=3\" target=\"_blank\">WebMD</a>.#@:", "monkfish": "Pregnant women can enjoy monkfish as part of the six six-ounce servings of moderate mercury cooked seafood they eat per month. The <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby caused by high levels of mercury. Monkfish is in the class of fish considered to have a moderate amount of mercury according to the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/fishmercury.htm\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat monkfish if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "rapini": "Rapini is safe for pregnant women to eat. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their rapini prior to eating it. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "brussel sprouts": "According to <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/529137-can-pregnant-women-eat-brussels-sprouts/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, brussel sprouts are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their brussel sprouts prior to eating them. Unwashed produce may contain harmful bacteria and parasites that can cause food-borne diseases such as toxoplasmosis and listeriosis according to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/resourcesforyou/consumers/ucm114299\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancycomplications/toxoplasmosis.html\" target=\"_blank\">American Pregnancy Association</a>.&nbsp;#@:", "meringue": "Meringue that is made with pasteurized eggs and is fully cooked is safe to eat. <a href=\"http://www.babymed.com/food-and-nutrition/raw-eggs-during-pregnancy\">BabyMed </a>and the <a href=\"http://www.americanpregnancy.org/pregnancyhealth/foodstoavoid.html/\">American Pregnancy Association</a> state that raw or unpasteurized eggs may contain bacteria such as E. coli or Salmonella, which may be harmful to both a pregnant woman and her baby. #@:", "pollock": "Pregnant women can enjoy pollock as part of the two six-ounce servings of low mercury cooked seafood they eat per week. Due to high levels of mercury, the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a> recommends a limit on the amount and kind of seafood pregnant women ingest to prevent harm to themselves and their baby. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115662.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>,&nbsp;pollock is in the class of fish considered to have the lowest amount of mercury. Additionally, pregnant women should only eat pollock if it is fully cooked. According to the <a href=\"http://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/HealthEducators/ucm082294.htm\" target=\"_blank\">FDA</a>, pregnant women should not eat any raw or undercooked seafood and should cook fish to at least 145&deg;F.&nbsp;#@:", "paneer cheese": "According to the <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com.au/pregnancy/nutrition/foodsafety/cheeseexpert/\" target=\"_blank\">Baby Center</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"http://www.livestrong.com/article/277231-cheeses-to-eat-when-pregnant/\" target=\"_blank\">Livestrong</a>, hard cheeses such as Paneer Cheese are considered safe for pregnant women because they are generally made with pasteurized milk or are cooked at high temperatures. To be certain, pregnant women should check the label to be sure that the cheese is made with pasteurized milk. #@:", "persimmons": "According to <a href=\"http://www.babycenter.com/0_fruits-and-vegetables-in-your-pregnancy-diet_1695.bc\" target=\"_blank\">Babycenter.com</a>, persimmons are a safe and healthy choice during pregnancy. However, it is essential that pregnant women wash their persim